The paper deals with the problem of arranging disks in the plane to maximize their visible perimeter, which is a problem in computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also involves analyzing the density of point sets and their distances, which are topics in computational geometry and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The use of algorithms and data structures to solve the problem falls under computer science theory (cs.DS). The paper also involves graph theory and combinatorics, which are subfields of computer science (cs.GR) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper discusses the implications of the results for practical applications, such as sensor networks, which falls under the subfield of computer systems and networking (cs.SI).
